(61, 1, '2016-02-04 09:54:44', '2016-02-04 08:54:44', 'A parameter of type radio button can be pre-filled with custom values via the web app or via a PreRunEntryPoint.\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Via the web app</strong></span>\r\nThis can be done on the Parameters tab of the formula. Click on the \'values\' link.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/docs/input-radio-1.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nHere you can set the values for the radio button.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/docs/input-radio-2.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nAfter adding our values, we can set a default value by clicking on the \'Set Default Value\' link.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/docs/input-radio-3.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIn the Set Default Value overlay, click in the Default Value field and select the desired default value, click on the green check to save your result.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/docs/input-radio-4.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nNow when we click the \'Hello World\' button well see our active values with a radio button.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/docs/input-radio-5.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nTo retrieve the selected value in our script we have to read the FormulaParameterValue with the id we retrieved.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n<pre class="lang:c# decode:true EnlighterJSRAW " data-enlighter-language="csharp" data-enlighter-theme="classic">using TenForce.Execution.Api2; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.Api2;\r\n\r\nnamespace Tenforce.Execution.Addins.MyAddin\r\n{\r\n public class HelloWorld : Script&lt;ScriptContext&gt;\r\n {\r\n private IApi Api { get { return Factory.Instance; } } \r\n private IFieldRetriever FieldRetriever { get; set; } \r\n\r\n public HelloWorld() \r\n {\r\n FieldRetriever = new FieldHandler.DefaultFieldRetriever(); \r\n }\r\n\r\n [EntryPoint]\r\n public void RunCode()\r\n {\r\n // Find the selected value \r\n var value = Api.FormulaParameterValues.Read(ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("Test"));\r\n // Show value \r\n AddFeedBack(value.ScreenLabel);\r\n }\r\n }\r\n}</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Via PreRunEntryPoint in a script</strong></span>\r\nWe can also fill the values at runtime. To do this we need to have a method which is marked as [PreRunEntryPoint]. This method is called before the overlay with the parameters is shown. In this method we retrieve a list of our formula parameters and we can fill our parameters with values. This method only works for Action button and AdministrationMacro.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n<pre class="EnlighterJSRAW " data-enlighter-language="csharp" data-enlighter-theme="classic">using System; \r\nusing System.Collections.Generic; \r\nusing System.Linq; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2.Objects;\r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting;\r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.Api2;\r\n\r\nnamespace Tenforce.Execution.Addins.MyAddin\r\n{\r\n public class HelloWorld : Script&lt;ScriptContext&gt;\r\n {\r\n private IApi Api { get { return Factory.Instance; } }\r\n private IFieldRetriever FieldRetriever { get; set; }\r\n private readonly String[] _animals;\r\n\r\n public HelloWorld() \r\n { \r\n FieldRetriever = new FieldHandler.DefaultFieldRetriever(); \r\n _animals = new[] { "Cat", "Dog", "Mouse", "Horse" }; \r\n }\r\n\r\n [PreRunEntryPoint]\r\n public List&lt;FormulaParameter&gt; PreRun()\r\n {\r\n var parameters = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("FormulaParameters") as List&lt;FormulaParameter&gt; ?? new List&lt;FormulaParameter&gt;(); // Find the parameter in the list \r\n var testParameter = parameters.FirstOrDefault(p =&gt; p.Name.Equals("Test", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase)); \r\n if (testParameter == null) return parameters; // Put the array into an array of FormulaParameterValue, setting the array index as Id \r\n\r\n testParameter.FormulaParameterValues = _animals.Select((a, i) =&gt; // string, index \r\n new FormulaParameterValue\r\n {\r\n Active = true, // Active value \r\n Formula = testParameter.Formula,\r\n FormulaParameter = testParameter, // Start from 1 since we can not use 0 as Id \r\n Id = i + 1,\r\n Name = a, // Name of our value \r\n ScreenLabel = a, // Screenlabel of our value \r\n Sequence = i\r\n }).ToArray(); \r\n\r\n // Default \r\n testParameter.DefaultValue = "1"; // Cat \r\n\r\n return parameters;\r\n }\r\n\r\n [EntryPoint]\r\n public void RunCode()\r\n {\r\n var animalIndex = int.Parse((string)ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("Test")) - 1;\r\n AddFeedBack(_animals[animalIndex]);\r\n }\r\n }\r\n}</pre>\r\nTo set the default value we have to set the Id of value. In this example we fill the values with values from an array we defined. We use the index (+1, because we cannot use Id 0) of the value as Id.', 'RadioButton', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'radiobutton', '', '', '2016-02-09 15:05:34', '2016-02-09 14:05:34', '', 0, 'http://www.tenforce.com/portal/?post_type=inputs&#038;p=61', 0, 'inputs', '', 0),
