(258, 6, '2016-02-16 14:24:25', '2016-02-16 13:24:25', '<h1 id="example-script">Example script</h1>\r\n<h2 id="create-a-new-script">Create a new C# script in Visual Studio</h2>\r\nThe add-in template contains some example scripts. They are located under the Addin project in the Install folder. All scripts should be located under the Install folder. Select the Install folder, right click and select Add -&gt; New item\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-1.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIn the Add New Item screen, select one of the TenForce templates. AdminScript is the base template, you can go every direction with this one.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-2.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nGive your script a meaningful name like HelloWorld.cs and press the Add button.\r\n<h2 id="hello-world">\'Hello World\' script</h2>\r\nAs an example were going to create a hello world script. In the AdminScript which you just created, add the line<code>AddFeedBack("Hello World")</code>\r\n<pre class="lang:c# decode:true ">using System.Collections.Generic; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2.Objects; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.Api2; \r\n\r\nnamespace Tenforce.Execution.Addins.MyAddin \r\n{\r\n public class HelloWorld : Script&lt;ScriptContext&gt;\r\n {\r\n private IApi Api { get { return Factory.Instance; } }\r\n private IFieldRetriever FieldRetriever { get; set; }\r\n\r\n public HelloWorld()\r\n {\r\n FieldRetriever = new FieldHandler.DefaultFieldRetriever();\r\n } \r\n \r\n [EntryPoint]\r\n public void RunCode() \r\n {\r\n  AddFeedBack("Hello World"); \r\n }\r\n } \r\n}</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe RunCode method is the entry point of our script. This method will be called when the script is triggered.\r\n\r\nAddFeedBack is a method which will show feedback to the user. This method can also be useful while debugging a script.\r\n<h2 id="create-a-formula-">Create a \'formula\' in the web application</h2>\r\nTo add our code to pmOperation, we need to create a new formula. Goto http(s)://&lt;pmoperation url&gt;/config/formula or via Settings -&gt; Setup &amp; Configuration -&gt; Formula.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-3.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIn the formulas list, click on the Create new formula link at the bottom of the list.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-4.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can set a unique code, description, type, state and group for your formula.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-5.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your new formula. After saving, click on the code of your formula to open the formula detail page.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-6.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nSelect the version tab to create a formula version. Click on the Create new formula version link to create a new formula version.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-7.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can set a unique code, valid date, valid time, description and language for your formula version.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-8.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your formula version. After saving, click on the MacroCode link to add your code.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-9.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new screen will popup where you can paste your formula code.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-10.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick save to save your code.\r\n<h2 id="create-custom-item-script">Create a \'custom item script\' in the web application</h2>\r\nBecause our example is of type custom item script, we also have to create a Custom Item Script for it in pmOperation. Navigate to http(s)://&lt;pmoperation url&gt;/config/customitemscript or via Settings -&gt; Workspaces and their setup -&gt; Custom Item Script.\r\n\r\nClick on \'Create new item script\' at the bottom of the list.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-11.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can set a unique code, title, description, state and formula for your custom item script.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-12.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your custom item script.\r\n<h2 id="create-a-button">Create an \'action button\' in the web application</h2>\r\nWere going to attach our custom item script to a button on a list. Therefore we need to go to the list settings of any list.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-13.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the Action buttons tab and click on the Create new item script link.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-14.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can set the button caption, item script, privileges, visibility and state for your action button.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-15.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your button. Now, go back to the list view and youll see the button you just created.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-16.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the button to execute our Hello World Code.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/example-17.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nCongratulations! You made your first script in pmOperation. Of course this is only a simple example and well go through the more advanced scripting techniques in the next chapters.\r\n<h1 id="formula-types"></h1>\r\n<h3 id="action-button">\'Action buttons\' in the web application</h3>\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-1.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nHere you can configure the code, the confirmation text and title for the overlay used by action buttons.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-2.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIf you set a confirmation text, this text will be shown in an overlay when you click an action button.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-3.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nAs you can see, the title and confirmation text used for the overlay is the one you supplied in the custom item script. The script behind the button is only executed when the user clicks the Execute button. Of course the confirmation text is optionally and if you dont set one the script will be executed immediately.\r\n\r\nYou can also provide parameters to an action button. These are configured on the formula. Click on the Parameters tab and click on the Create new formula parameter link.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-4.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can set the sequence, code, screen label, explanation, type and requirement for your formula parameter.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-5.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your formula parameter. Optionally you can set a default value after saving.\r\n\r\nWhen you click on the Hello World action button, you again get the overlay but now with the parameter you just added.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-6.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nThe parameter also shows the screen label and explanation you configured. You can input some text into the parameter. Press the Execute button to execute the script.\r\n\r\nThe parameter is passed to the EntryPoint of our script in ScriptContext.ScriptParameters and can be retrieved via the GetParameter method supplying the parameter code.\r\n<pre class="lang:c# decode:true">using TenForce.Execution.Api2; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting; \r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.Api2; \r\n\r\nnamespace Tenforce.Execution.Addins.MyAddin \r\n{\r\n public class HelloWorld : Script&lt;ScriptContext&gt;\r\n {\r\n private IApi Api { get { return Factory.Instance; } }\r\n private IFieldRetriever FieldRetriever { get; set; }\r\n \r\n public HelloWorld()\r\n {\r\n FieldRetriever = new FieldHandler.DefaultFieldRetriever();\r\n }\r\n \r\n [EntryPoint]\r\n public void RunCode()\r\n {\r\n var someText = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("SomeText") as string;\r\n AddFeedBack("Hello World");\r\n }\r\n } \r\n}</pre>\r\nParameters are always passed as type object so you have to cast it to a usable type yourself.\r\n\r\nDepending on where you clicked the button, on an item, list or smartlist, you also get those objects passed as a parameter. In our example we have set the visibility of our button to item, list and smartlist.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-7.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIf we click on the button in the list view, we can retrieve the list in our script by using:\r\n<pre><code>var list = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("List") as List;</code></pre>\r\nIf we click on the button on a smartlist, we can retrieve the smartlist by using:\r\n<pre><code>var smartList = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("SmartList") as SmartList;</code></pre>\r\nIf we click on the button on the item detail page, we can retrieve the item by using:\r\n<pre><code>var item = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("Item") as Item;</code></pre>\r\nYou can check where the button is clicked by checking the objects for null. E.g. Item and SmartList will be null if the button is clicked in list view.\r\n<h3>\'Event scripts\' in the web application</h3>\r\nFor event scripts only the code of the custom item script is actually used when configuring the event script on a list. Event scripts are configured on the custom Item Script tab in the list settings. Click on the Create new item script link.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-8.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nA new line will appear where you can configure the event, script, sequence and state.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-9.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nClick on the green check to save your custom item script.\r\n\r\nAfter saving you can configure the parameters by clicking on the parameters link of the corresponding custom item script.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-10.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nAn overlay will appear where you can configure the parameters.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-11.png" alt="" />\r\n\r\nUnlike on action buttons, the parameters on custom item scripts are not asked for when the script is triggered. Instead you can pre-configure them per list. This makes it possible to create generic scripts which have different parameter data per list.\r\n\r\nThe parameters are passed to the EntryPoint of our script in ScriptContext.ScriptParameters and can be retrieved via the GetParameter method supplying the parameter code.\r\n\r\nEvery event has a few default parameters passed by the application. This depends on which event is triggered. You can find more documentation on this in the Events chapter.', 'TenForce development walkthrough - Scripts', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'tenforce-development-walkthrough-scripts', '', '', '2016-04-26 08:57:12', '2016-04-26 07:57:12', '', 0, 'http://devcenter.tenforce.com/portal/?post_type=tutorials&#038;p=258', 0, 'tutorials', '', 0),
(259, 6, '2016-03-08 09:33:48', '2016-03-08 08:33:48', '<h1 id="introduction">Introduction</h1>\nScripting in pmOperation is done in C#. Therefore all development is done in Visual Studio.\n<h1 id="setting-up-development-environment">Setting up development environment</h1>\n<h2 id="visual-studio-2013">Visual Studio 2013</h2>\n<h3 id="installing-templates">Installing TenForce templates</h3>\nI have setup a private extension gallery for visual studio 2012. This way we can auto update our TenForce Addin templates inside Visual Studio.\nHere are the steps to configure it :\n<ul>\n	<li>Open Microsoft Visual Studio and go to \'Tools\' &gt; \'Extensions and Updates\'</li>\n	<li>Addthe TenforceGallery.reg(you can find it <a href="http://dev.tenforce.eu/tenforcegallery/tenforcegallery.reg" target="_blank">here</a>)</li>\n	<li>Inthe \'Online\' tab forthe \'TenForceGallery\', press the \'Download\' button to installthe \'TenForce API2 Templates\'</li>\n</ul>\n<a href="http://devcenter.tenforce.com/portal/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Capture_1.png" rel="attachment wp-att-260"><img class="alignnone wp-image-260" src="http://devcenter.tenforce.com/portal/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Capture_1-300x207.png" alt="Capture_1" width="468" height="323" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2 id="creating-an-add-in-project">Creating an add-in project</h2>\nFrom the Visual Studio menu select File -&gt; New project and select TenForce Addin (Api2).\n\n<img class="" src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-4.png" alt="" width="467" height="362" />\n\nPress \'OK\'. The add-in settings screen will popup.\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-5.png" alt="" />\n\n<dl><dt>Site ID</dt><dd>Put 0 in here.\n<strong>Addin ID\n</strong>Unique ID for your add-in.</dd></dl>Press \'Ok\' to create the add-in solution.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAfter creation of the project, set the Emulator project as startup project\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-6.png" alt="" />\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2 id="copy-application-assemblies">Copy application assemblies</h2>\nWe need the pmOperation assemblies because these are referenced in the add-in project. These assemblies contain the Api2 methods used in scripting. It is important to use the correct version of the assemblies. The version you use in your add-in project should be the same as the pmOperation version you use. You can find the pmOperation version on the bottom left when navigating to http(s)://&lt;pmoperation url&gt;/config.\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-7.png" alt="" />\n\nTo find out the assemblies version, right click on the assembly, select properties and navigate to the details tab.\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-8.png" alt="" />\n\nIn this example the 2.183.915.0 stands for\n<ul>\n	<li>2 = Major version</li>\n	<li>183 = Minor version</li>\n	<li>915 = Database version</li>\n	<li>0 = Patch version</li>\n</ul>\nUnder the directory &lt;add-in name&gt;\\&lt;add-in name&gt;, create a directory called dlls.\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/set-up-9.png" alt="" />\n\nCopy all .dll files from the pmOperation \\bin folder to the dlls folder.\n\n&nbsp;', 'TenForce development walkthrough - Visual Studio', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '92-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-03-08 09:33:48', '2016-03-08 08:33:48', '', 92, 'http://devcenter.tenforce.com/portal/92-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
