(348, 22, '2016-02-26 08:48:09', '2016-02-26 07:48:09', '<h2>Introduction to <code>git</code></h2>\r\nSubversion (aka svn) is a centralized revision control system.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/svn-is-centralized.png" alt="svn-is-centralized" />\r\n\r\n<code>git</code> on the other hand is decentralized. Decentralized revision control systems offer several advantages over centralized ones. However, working with <code>git</code> can be a little more complicated than working with <code>svn</code>.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/git-is-de-centralized.png" alt="git-is-de-centralized" />\r\n\r\nThe following tables show the <code>git</code> counterparts of <code>svn</code> commands (credits: <a href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines">http://git.or.cz/course/svn.html</a>)\r\n<table>\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th><code>git</code></th>\r\n<th><code>svn</code></th>\r\n<th>Remarks</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git clone url</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn checkout url</code></td>\r\n<td>Checking out a remote repository</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git checkout --track -b branch origin/branch</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn switch url</code></td>\r\n<td>Switching to a remote branch</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git pull</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn update</code></td>\r\n<td>Synchronizing with remote repository</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git merge branch</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn merge -r 20:HEAD http://example.com/svn/branches/branch</code></td>\r\n<td>Merging a branch</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git branch branch</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn copy http://example.com/svn/trunk http://example.com/svn/branches/branch</code></td>\r\n<td>Creating a new branch</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git log</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn log</code></td>\r\n<td>Browsing log (history)</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git add file</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn add file</code></td>\r\n<td>Adding a new file</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git rm file</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn rm file</code></td>\r\n<td>Removing a file</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git mv file</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn mv file</code></td>\r\n<td>Moving or renaming a file</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git status</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn status</code></td>\r\n<td>Checking status of working copy</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><code>git add .</code> &amp;&amp; <code>git commit</code> &amp;&amp; <code>git push</code></td>\r\n<td><code>svn commit</code></td>\r\n<td>Comming and publishing local changes</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><a id="git-online-resource" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#git-online-resource"></a><code>git</code> online resource</h3>\r\nFor a complete list of commands, please check <code>git</code> documentation at <a href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines">https://git-scm.com/documentation</a>\r\n\r\nYou are also encouraged to consult other online resources:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.git-tower.com/blog/git-for-subversion-users-cheat-sheet" rel="nofollow">Git for Subversion Users - A <em>Cheat Sheet</em></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://try.github.io" rel="nofollow"><em>interactive</em> tutorial</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.git-tower.com/learn" rel="nofollow">e-book and <em>video</em> course</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://gitimmersion.com" rel="nofollow"><em>interactive</em> tutorial</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://git-scm.com/book/en" rel="nofollow">free downloadable <em>e-book</em></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><a id="gui-git-client-sourcetree" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#gui-git-client-sourcetree"></a>GUI <code>git</code> client = SourceTree</h3>\r\nOnce you have a solid understanding of the working of <code>git</code> and common workflows, you may want to actually use a GUI <code>git</code> client. In TenForce, we opted for SourceTree from Atlassian <a href="https://www.sourcetreeapp.com/" rel="nofollow">download SourceTree</a>.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2><a id="workflow" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#workflow"></a>Workflow</h2>\r\nIn this section, we provide an overview of a flow for processing different sorts of activities within our team. We\'ll attempt to cover projects, service requests and support tickets.\r\n\r\nThe above activities share a few characteristics; for one, they change the state of the code base. Such changes may result in visible changes of the behavior of the application from the customer\'s perspective.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow.png" alt="workflow" />\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/deployment-planning.png" alt="deployment-planning" />\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow-concurrent-development.png" alt="workflow-concurrent-development" />\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow-in-git.png" alt="workflow-in-git" />\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong>Git tips and tricks\r\n</strong>\r\n<h2>Don\'t <code>rebase</code></h2>\r\n<code>git</code> provides two flavors of merging branches; with and without rebasing. Rebasing has been a hot discussion topic within TenForce and outside. Atlassian wrote a nice tutorial page on the different between merge and rebase <a href="https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/merging-vs-rebasing" rel="nofollow">Merging vs. Rebasing</a>.\r\n\r\nMy (Osman) personal take on the matter is: don\'t rebase unless you know what you are doing. if you rebase and get into trouble, Sven and Tim will gladly help you out. There are a few cases where I think rebasing is safe:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>You may do whatever you want in your <em>private</em> (reads: nobody has checked it out) branches; including rebasing</li>\r\n	<li>there is hardly a second safe situation for rebasing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2><a id="visual-studio-built-in-git-client-is-not-supported" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-tips-and-tricks#visual-studio-built-in-git-client-is-not-supported"></a>Visual Studio built-in <code>git</code> client is not supported</h2>\r\nI (Osman) don\'t provide support for the above mentioned client for the simple reason that I am not familiar with it.\r\n<h2><a id="synchronize-often-with-the-remote-repository" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-tips-and-tricks#synchronize-often-with-the-remote-repository"></a>Synchronize often with the remote repository</h2>\r\nIf you are working in a team on the same repository, you don\'t want to isolate yourself for extended amount of time. Go ahead a fetch (and pull, for this matter) your colleauges\' work everymorning!', 'Git guidelines', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'git-guidelines', '', '', '2016-04-26 08:53:36', '2016-04-26 07:53:36', '', 0, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/?post_type=tutorials&#038;p=348', 0, 'tutorials', '', 0),
(349, 22, '2016-02-26 08:49:32', '2016-02-26 07:49:32', '<h2>Introduction to <code>git</code></h2>\nSubversion (aka svn) is a centralized revision control system.\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/svn-is-centralized.png" alt="svn-is-centralized" />\n\n<code>git</code> on the other hand is decentralized. Decentralized revision control systems offer several advantages over centralized ones. However, working with <code>git</code> can be a little more complicated than working with <code>svn</code>.\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/git-is-de-centralized.png" alt="git-is-de-centralized" />\n\nThe following tables show the <code>git</code> counterparts of <code>svn</code> commands (credits: <a href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines">http://git.or.cz/course/svn.html</a>)\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th><code>git</code></th>\n<th><code>svn</code></th>\n<th>Remarks</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git clone url</code></td>\n<td><code>svn checkout url</code></td>\n<td>Checking out a remote repository</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git checkout --track -b branch origin/branch</code></td>\n<td><code>svn switch url</code></td>\n<td>Switching to a remote branch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git pull</code></td>\n<td><code>svn update</code></td>\n<td>Synchronizing with remote repository</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git merge branch</code></td>\n<td><code>svn merge -r 20:HEAD http://example.com/svn/branches/branch</code></td>\n<td>Merging a branch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git branch branch</code></td>\n<td><code>svn copy http://example.com/svn/trunk http://example.com/svn/branches/branch</code></td>\n<td>Creating a new branch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git log</code></td>\n<td><code>svn log</code></td>\n<td>Browsing log (history)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git add file</code></td>\n<td><code>svn add file</code></td>\n<td>Adding a new file</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git rm file</code></td>\n<td><code>svn rm file</code></td>\n<td>Removing a file</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git mv file</code></td>\n<td><code>svn mv file</code></td>\n<td>Moving or renaming a file</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git status</code></td>\n<td><code>svn status</code></td>\n<td>Checking status of working copy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code>git add .</code> &amp;&amp; <code>git commit</code> &amp;&amp; <code>git push</code></td>\n<td><code>svn commit</code></td>\n<td>Comming and publishing local changes</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3><a id="git-online-resource" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#git-online-resource"></a><code>git</code> online resource</h3>\nFor a complete list of commands, please check <code>git</code> documentation at <a href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines">https://git-scm.com/documentation</a>\n\nYou are also encouraged to consult other online resources:\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://www.git-tower.com/blog/git-for-subversion-users-cheat-sheet" rel="nofollow">Git for Subversion Users - A <em>Cheat Sheet</em></a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://try.github.io" rel="nofollow"><em>interactive</em> tutorial</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://www.git-tower.com/learn" rel="nofollow">e-book and <em>video</em> course</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://gitimmersion.com" rel="nofollow"><em>interactive</em> tutorial</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://git-scm.com/book/en" rel="nofollow">free downloadable <em>e-book</em></a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><a id="gui-git-client-sourcetree" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#gui-git-client-sourcetree"></a>GUI <code>git</code> client = SourceTree</h3>\nOnce you have a solid understanding of the working of <code>git</code> and common workflows, you may want to actually use a GUI <code>git</code> client. In TenForce, we opted for SourceTree from Atlassian <a href="https://www.sourcetreeapp.com/" rel="nofollow">download SourceTree</a>.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2><a id="workflow" class="anchor" href="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/git-guidelines#workflow"></a>Workflow</h2>\nIn this section, we provide an overview of a flow for processing different sorts of activities within our team. We\'ll attempt to cover projects, service requests and support tickets.\n\nThe above activities share a few characteristics; for one, they change the state of the code base. Such changes may result in visible changes of the behavior of the application from the customer\'s perspective.\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow.png" alt="workflow" />\n\n<hr />\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/deployment-planning.png" alt="deployment-planning" />\n\n<hr />\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow-concurrent-development.png" alt="workflow-concurrent-development" />\n\n<hr />\n\n<img src="https://git.tenforce.com/pmx-ps/PSCockpit/wikis/images/workflow-in-git.png" alt="workflow-in-git" />\n\n<hr />\n\n&nbsp;', 'Git guidelines', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '348-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-02-26 08:49:32', '2016-02-26 07:49:32', '', 348, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/348-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(351, 6, '2016-03-01 15:36:11', '2016-03-01 14:36:11', 'A data grid is acustom field in which a table or grid of data can be put. A formula of type \'DataGridScript\'determines whichdata, columns and options are shown.\r\n<h4><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Addthe custom field(s) on the list(s) in the web application</strong></span></h4>\r\nGo to the \'customize\' page of the list(s) and create a new \'data grid\' field: select the correct \'data grid\'formulaand give the field a unique code and screen label.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAn example of a \'DataGridScript\' formula is:\r\n<pre class="EnlighterJSRAW " data-enlighter-language="csharp">using System.Collections.Generic;\r\nusing System.Linq;\r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2;\r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2.Objects;\r\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.DataGrid;\r\n\r\nnamespace TenForce.Execution.Scripting\r\n{\r\npublic class ExampleDataGrid : Script&lt;ScriptContext&gt;\r\n {\r\n private readonly IApi _api = Factory.Instance;\r\n\r\n [EntryPoint]\r\n public void RunCode()\r\n {\r\n var dataGrid = ScriptContext as DataGridScriptContext;\r\n switch (dataGrid.CurrentAction)\r\n {\r\n case DataGridScriptAction.Generate:\r\n   GenerateData(dataGrid);\r\n   break;\r\n\r\n case DataGridScriptAction.GetColumns:\r\n   dataGrid.ResultDataColumns = GetDataColumns();\r\n   break;\r\n\r\n case DataGridScriptAction.GetColumnEntries:\r\n   dataGrid.ResultColumnEntries = GetColumnEntries("manager");\r\n   break;\r\n }\r\n }\r\n\r\n private static Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt; GetColumnEntries(string columnCode)\r\n {\r\n if (columnCode == "manager")\r\n {\r\n  return new []{1,65}.Select(id =&gt; new User{Id = id, FirstName=id.ToString() }).ToDictionary(user =&gt; user.Id.ToString(), user =&gt; user.FirstName);\r\n }\r\n else\r\n  return new Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt;();\r\n }\r\n\r\n private void GenerateData(DataGridScriptContext dataGrid)\r\n {\r\n //Settings of the data grid\r\n dataGrid.HasFilter = true;\r\n dataGrid.NumberOfObjectsPerPage = 10;\r\n\r\n //Datainthecolumns ofthedatagrid\r\n dataGrid.ResultDataColumns = GetDataColumns();\r\n\r\n //Get the users\r\n var allUsers = _api.Users.ListAll().OrderBy(u =&gt; u.FirstName).ThenBy(u =&gt; u.LastName).ToList();\r\n allUsers.RemoveAll(u =&gt; FilterResult(u, dataGrid));\r\n\r\n //Data in the rows of the data grid\r\n dataGrid.ResultDataRows = new List&lt;Row&gt;();\r\n foreach (User user in allUsers)\r\n {\r\n  dataGrid.ResultDataRows.Add(GenerateRow(user));\r\n }\r\n }\r\n\r\n private static Row GenerateRow(User user)\r\n {\r\n return new Row\r\n {\r\n Id = 1,\r\n Link = "/config/persons/" + user.Id,\r\n Properties = new List&lt;KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;&gt;\r\n {\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("id", user.Id.ToString()),\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("fname", user.FirstName),\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("lname", user.LastName),\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("login", user.Login),\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("email", user.Email),\r\n new KeyValuePair&lt;string, string&gt;("manager", user.FirstName),\r\n }\r\n };\r\n }\r\n\r\n//Thecolumns ofthedatagrid\r\n private static List&lt;DataColumn&gt; GetDataColumns()\r\n {\r\n return new List&lt;DataColumn&gt;()\r\n {\r\n new DataColumn\r\n {\r\n Code = "fname",\r\n ColumnType = ColumnType.link,\r\n ColumnWidth = ColumnWidth.md,\r\n ScreenLabel = "First Name"\r\n },\r\n new DataColumn\r\n {\r\n Code = "lname",\r\n ColumnType = ColumnType.text,\r\n ColumnWidth = ColumnWidth.md,\r\n ScreenLabel = "Last Name",\r\n IsReadonly = true\r\n },\r\n new DataColumn\r\n {\r\n Code = "login",\r\n ColumnType = ColumnType.text,\r\n ColumnWidth = ColumnWidth.md,\r\n ScreenLabel = "Login"\r\n },\r\n new DataColumn\r\n {\r\n Code = "email",\r\n ColumnType = ColumnType.text,\r\n ColumnWidth = ColumnWidth.var,\r\n ScreenLabel = "Email Address"\r\n },\r\n new DataColumn\r\n {\r\n Code = "manager",\r\n ColumnType = ColumnType.combobox,\r\n ColumnWidth = ColumnWidth.md,\r\n ScreenLabel = "Manager",\r\n DisplayedProperty = "manager"\r\n }\r\n };\r\n }\r\n\r\n public bool FilterResult(User p, DataGridScriptContext dataGrid)\r\n {\r\n bool remove = false;\r\n if (p == null || dataGrid.Filter == null)\r\n  return true;\r\n\r\n foreach (DataColumn column in GetDataColumns())\r\n {\r\n if (remove)\r\n {\r\n  break;\r\n }\r\n var key = column.Code;\r\n string value;\r\n if (!dataGrid.Filter.TryGetValue(key, out value) || string.IsNullOrEmpty(value))\r\n  continue;\r\n\r\n switch (column.Code.ToLower())\r\n {\r\n case "lname":\r\n   if (!p.LastName.ToLower().Contains(value)) remove = true;\r\n   break;\r\n\r\n case "fname":\r\n if (!p.FirstName.ToLower().Contains(value)) remove = true;\r\n break;\r\n\r\n case "email":\r\n if (!p.Email.ToLower().Contains(value)) remove = true;\r\nbreak;\r\n\r\n case "login":\r\n if (!p.Login.ToLower().Contains(value)) remove = true;\r\n break;\r\n }\r\n }\r\n\r\n return remove;\r\n }\r\n }\r\n}</pre>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Data Grid', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'data-grid', '', '', '2016-04-26 08:43:31', '2016-04-26 07:43:31', '', 0, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/?post_type=tutorials&#038;p=351', 0, 'tutorials', '', 0),
