(431, 9, '2016-04-12 16:24:43', '2016-04-12 15:24:43', '<h1>WHY</h1>\r\nTo continuously maintain and improve the quality of our work we aim at delivering standardized quality code.\r\n\r\nGood quality code is:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Readable</li>\r\n	<li>understandable</li>\r\n	<li>Efficient</li>\r\n	<li>maintainable</li>\r\n	<li>Conform standards</li>\r\n	<li>Using best-practices</li>\r\n	<li>.......</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOne of the mechanisms of quality control is doing <strong>code-reviews</strong>.\r\nThe purpose of a code review is two folded:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Improve the quality, efficiency and standardization of our code.</li>\r\n	<li>Educating developers.\r\nBy having (your) code reviewed, people will learn, evolve, learn, evolve...</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHaving said that: the code review is focused on the <em>CODE</em> not on the <em>PROGRAMMER</em>!\r\n<h2>HOW</h2>\r\nCode reviews will be done on regular basis for all projects and during the course of the project.\r\n\r\nIn the projects overview in Tracker (<span style="color: #3366ff;"><a style="color: #3366ff;" href="https://texectracker.tenforce.com/texectracker/workspace/383/3176l" target="_blank">https://texectracker.tenforce.com/texectracker/workspace/383/3176l</a></span>) theres a new tab (per project) called Code Reviews.\r\nHere, we keep track of the code reviews performed and the general findings. More specific details of certain code aspects to improve, will be added as comments in GIT.\r\n\r\nReviews are done, taking a basic checklist as starting point (but of course not necessarily limited to that checklist, only).\r\n<h2>WHAT</h2>\r\nThe checklist of items which are reviewed can be found here: <span style="color: #3366ff;"><a style="color: #3366ff;" href="https://texectracker.tenforce.com/texectracker/workspace/383/3208l/" target="_blank">https://texectracker.tenforce.com/texectracker/workspace/383/3208l/</a></span>\r\n\r\nThere are 3 categories of Rules:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Mandatory</strong>\r\nNo discussion. This is a \'holy\' rule to respect.\r\nExamples are:\r\n<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">\r\n	<li>Check for null references</li>\r\n	<li>Remove alldebug statements</li>\r\n	<li>Add code comments</li>\r\n	<li>Use correct branching in GIT</li>\r\n	<li>Functions should contain less than 100 lines of code</li>\r\n	<li>.....</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Recommended</strong>\r\nStrongly recommended guideline.Do not diverge from this unless you have a very (very!) good reason.\r\nExamples are:\r\n<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">\r\n	<li>Use object oriented code</li>\r\n	<li>Use common add-ins</li>\r\n	<li>Retrieve data only once</li>\r\n	<li>Declare local variables right before they are used</li>\r\n	<li>....</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Optional\r\n</strong>Best practice guidelines. Not necessarily wrong or poor coding, but respecting these rules, results in better quality code.\r\nExamples are:\r\n<ul style="list-style-type: circle;">\r\n	<li>Source files should contain less then 1000 lines of code</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid duplicate savings of the same object</li>\r\n	<li>....</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>WHEN</h2>\r\nCode reviews will be done throughout a project.\r\n\r\nThere will be several ways to initiate a code-reviews.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Upon request of the developer\r\nWhenever you feel you may need some insight or help in analyzing your code, do call out for a code review.</li>\r\n	<li>Upon request of the project manager or PS projects team lead (Andr)</li>\r\n	<li>Upon request of the PS support team lead (Tonny)\r\nE.g. when the project is about to deliver something in production.</li>\r\n	<li>Randomly\r\nOnce in a while, well just pick some project/code to have a look at.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Code reviews', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'code-reviews', '', '', '2016-04-26 08:25:29', '2016-04-26 07:25:29', '', 0, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/?post_type=tutorials&#038;p=431', 0, 'tutorials', '', 0),
(434, 6, '2016-04-13 09:37:59', '2016-04-13 08:37:59', '<h1 id="formula-types">Formula types</h1>\nThere are several kind of formula types in pmOperation, each with their own purpose.\n<ul>\n	<li>AdministrationMacro</li>\n	<li>AlertMacro</li>\n	<li>ConsolidationMacro</li>\n	<li>CustomItemScriptMacro</li>\n	<li>DataGridScript</li>\n	<li>DataTransformationMacro</li>\n	<li>FieldScriptMacro</li>\n	<li>IndicatorCalculationMacro</li>\n	<li>LibraryFunction</li>\n	<li>ReportScript</li>\n	<li>SearchScript</li>\n	<li>SourceFormulaMacro</li>\n	<li>UserScript</li>\n	<li>WorkspaceCreationScript</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<h2 id="customitemscriptmacro">CustomItemScriptMacro</h2>\nThis formula type is used for event scripts and action buttons. After adding the formula, you also have to add a Custom Item Script in Settings -&gt; Workspaces and their setup -&gt; Custom Item Script.\n<h2 id="libraryfunction">LibraryFunction</h2>\nIn formulas of type LibraryFunction you can define objects that can be used by all other formulas.\n<h2 id="administrationmacro">AdministrationMacro</h2>\nAn AdministrationMacro is a formula which is comparable to an Action button, except that it is only accessible by administrators by default. Instead of on a list, AdministrationMacros are defined in Settings -&gt; Setup &amp; Configuration -&gt; Administration Script.\n\n<img src="http://dev.tenforce.com/img/dev-tut/formula-12.png" alt="" />\n\nHere you can create new administration script or execute an existing one. Parameters on AdministrationMacros work the same way as on an Action button. An overlay pops up asking for the parameters.\n\nThe parameters are passed to the EntryPoint of our script in ScriptContext.ScriptParameters and can be retrieved via the GetParameter method supplying the parameter code.\n<h2 id="customfieldscriptmacro">FieldScriptMacro</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">DataGridScript</h2>\nThis formula type is used for custom fields of type \'data grid\':you can define whichdata and columns of a table or grid of data are shown and which options are set. After adding the formula, you can selectit as formulafora custom field of type \'data grid\'.\n<h2>IndicatorCalculationMacro</h2>\nAn IndicatorCalculationMacro is a formula that can be used byindicators. When the formula is added, it can be selected as formula\n\n<span style="font-size: 29px; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.2069;">AlertMacro</span>\n\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro"></h2>\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">ReportScript</h2>\n(TODO)\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro"></h2>\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">ConsolidationMacro</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">DataTransformationMacro</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">SourceFormulaMacro</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">SearchScript</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">UserScript</h2>\n(TODO)\n<h2 id="indicatorcalculationmacro">WorkspaceCreationScript</h2>\n(TODO)\n\n&nbsp;', 'Formula types', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '262-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-04-13 09:37:59', '2016-04-13 08:37:59', '', 262, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/262-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(435, 6, '2016-04-14 13:21:36', '2016-04-14 12:21:36', 'Processes that have to be calculatedin a periodic way, can be scheduled automatically by using indicators. Examples of these processes are: generation of reports, tracking of KPI\'s, import of data or files, processingemails from an inbox, ...\n<h3>Indicator templates and indicators</h3>\nAn indicator template should be defined first, before an indicator can be created. Indicator templates use a formula of type \'IndicatorCalculationMacro\', and have a specific (calculation) frequency. The formulacontains the logic of the processto be performed, and the frequencydefines when itshould be calculated. Also a unique code, screen label and description shouldbe added to define an indicator template.\nGo to \'<span class="ph-breadcrumb-first">Settings\' &gt; \'</span><span class="ph-breadcrumb">Indicators and Thresholds\' &gt; \'</span><span class="ph-breadcrumb">Indicator Templates\' to define a new indicator template.</span>\n<h4>Calculation frequency</h4>\nA calculation frequency is defined by a reference date, reference time, a delta time and delta type (i.e. minutes, (work) hours, (work) days, weeks, months, quarters, years), next to aunique code, screen label, description and sequence.\n<em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Example</span></em>: Anindicator will be calculated every (1) work day at 20h, starting the 1st of April 2016 by setting these values:reference date = 01/04/2016; reference time = 20:00, delta time = 1; delta type = work days.\nA new calculation frequency can be defined under\'<span class="ph-breadcrumb-first">Settings\' &gt; \'</span><span class="ph-breadcrumb">Indicators and Thresholds\' &gt; \'</span>Calculation Frequency\'<span class="ph-breadcrumb">.</span>\n<h4></h4>\n<h4>Indicators</h4>\nIndicators, inherited from an indicator template, can be linkedto a workspace or a list, depending on the logic behind.\n<em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Example:</span></em>An indicator that counts daily how many \'critical\' items (from multiple lists)are still in an open (active) status, will belinked to the workspace. A daily import of a certain type of items is calculated via an indicator linked to thatlist.\n\nTo create a new indicator linked to a list (or a workspace) go to the settings of that list (or workspace) and then to the \'indicator\' tab. Press the \'add anindicator\' link (for a new workspace indicator \'custom dashboard\' should be selected) and selected the correct indicator template. Activate the indicator, and it will be calculated as scheduled.\n<h4>Indicator calculation group</h4>\nAn indicator should be linked to a calculation group\n\nGo to \'<span class="ph-breadcrumb-first">Settings\' &gt; \'</span><span class="ph-breadcrumb">Indicators and Thresholds\' &gt; \'</span><span class="ph-breadcrumb">Indicator Calculation Group\' to define a new calculation group or set another group as default.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAn example of an indicator script, counting the number of created audits, is:\n<pre class="EnlighterJSRAW" data-enlighter-language="csharp">using System;\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\nusing System.Globalization;\nusing System.Linq;\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2;\nusing TenForce.Execution.Api2.Objects;\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting;\nusing TenForce.Execution.Scripting.Api2;\n\nnamespace TenForce.Execution.AddIns.Belgacom\n{\n public class Indicator : Script&lt;InCaScriptContext2&gt;\n {\n protected IApi Api { get; private set; }\n\n [EntryPoint]\n public virtual void RunCode()\n {\n try\n {\n Execute();\n }\n catch (Exception ex)\n {\n SetScriptContextResult(ex);\n }\n }\n\n public void Execute()\n {\n var limitTitle = ScriptContext.ScriptParameters.GetParameter("title") as string;\n\n Api = Factory.Instance;\n var lib = new BelgacomLibrary(Api);\n\n var wss = Api.Workspaces.ListAll();\n var allAudits = wss.Select(ws =&gt; lib.GetWorkspaceListId(ws, "Audits")).ToList(); // \'Audits\' list\n allAudits.RemoveAll(i =&gt; i &lt;= 0);\n\n //FIlter to only count new created audits\n var itemHistoryFilter = new ItemHistoryFilter\n {\n FromDateTime = DateTime.Today.AddDays(-1),\n ToDateTime = DateTime.Today,\n ItemFields = new List&lt;ItemField&gt;\n {\n new ItemField {FieldId = "id", Type = "ItemId"},\n new ItemField {FieldId = "SF7"},\n }.ToArray(),\n Lists = allAudits.ConvertAll(a =&gt; new List {Id = a}).ToArray()\n };\n Api.ItemHistoryLines.GetItemHistoryLinesByItemHistoryFilter(itemHistoryFilter);\n var itemHistoryLines = new List&lt;ItemHistoryLine&gt;(itemHistoryFilter.ItemHistoryLines);\n\n var fromDate = itemHistoryFilter.FromDateTime == DateTime.MinValue ? DateTime.Today : itemHistoryFilter.FromDateTime;\n var toDate = itemHistoryFilter.ToDateTime == DateTime.MinValue ? DateTime.Today : itemHistoryFilter.ToDateTime;\n\n var created = new Dictionary&lt;Item, DateTime&gt;();\n foreach(var ihl in itemHistoryLines)\n {\n Item fi;\n if(created.Keys.Any(i =&gt; i.Id == ihl.Item.Id)) continue;\n\n if (ihl.ItemField.Equals("SF7") \n &amp;&amp; (ihl.NewValue ?? string.Empty).Equals("502"))\n created.Add(Api.Items.Read(ihl.Item.Id), ihl.Timestamp);\n\n else if (ihl.ItemField.Equals("id") \n &amp;&amp; !string.IsNullOrEmpty(ihl.NewValue) \n &amp;&amp; (fi = Api.Items.Read(ihl.Item.Id)).ItemFields.First(f =&gt; f.FieldId == "SF7").Value.Equals("502"))\n created.Add(fi, ihl.Timestamp);\n }\n\n ScriptContext.RootCauseHeaderText = "Audits created between " + fromDate.ToShortDateString() + " and " + toDate.ToShortDateString();\n ScriptContext.RootCauseColumns.Add(new RootCauseColumn("Audit number", RootCauseFieldType.ItemLink));\n ScriptContext.RootCauseColumns.Add(new RootCauseColumn("Created on", RootCauseFieldType.DateTime));\n ScriptContext.RootCauseColumns.Add(new RootCauseColumn("Title", RootCauseFieldType.Link));\n ScriptContext.RootCauseDetail.Clear();\n\n foreach (var item in created)\n {\n var fh = lib.FieldHandler(item.Key);\n if(!string.IsNullOrEmpty(limitTitle) &amp;&amp; !fh.GetString("SF2").Equals(limitTitle))\n  continue;\n\n ScriptContext.RootCauseDetail.Add(new RootCauseData\n {\n FieldData01 = fh.Item.Id.ToString(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture),\n FieldData02 = item.Value.ToShortDateString(),\n FieldData03 = fh.GetString("SF2")\n });\n }\n ScriptContext.RootCauseFooterText = "Found " + ScriptContext.RootCauseDetail.Count + " audits";\n\n SetScriptContextResult(ScriptContext.RootCauseDetail.Count, "{0} audits created");\n }\n\n protected void SetScriptContextResult(Exception ex)\n {\n SetScriptContextResult(false, -1, ex.Message);\n }\n\n protected void SetScriptContextResult(int result, string message)\n {\n SetScriptContextResult(true, result, message);\n }\n\n protected void SetScriptContextResult(bool success, int result, string message)\n {\n message = string.Format(message ?? "{0}", result);\n message = message.Substring(0, Math.Min(80, message.Length));\n\n ScriptContext.ResultStatusString = message;\n ScriptContext.ResultType = ScriptResultType.Integer;\n ScriptContext.Result = result;\n ScriptContext.Status = (ScriptStatus)(success ? 1 : 2); // 1 = Done, 2 = DoneWithErrors\n ScriptContext.Indicator.CalculationResultStatus = new CalculationResultStatus { Id = success ? 1 : 2 }; // 1 = Ok, 2 = Macro Error\n ScriptContext.Indicator.CalculationResultStatusString = message;\n }\n }\n}\n\n</pre>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Indicators', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '402-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-04-14 13:21:36', '2016-04-14 12:21:36', '', 402, 'http://tenforce.konstantinkharlov.com/402-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
